Written evidence submitted by the Office of the Children’s Commissioner (LAI 0023)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Access to justice under the[bold] UN Convention on the Rights of the Child[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]‘…the child shall in particular be provided the opportunity to be heard in any judicial or administrative proceedings affecting the child, either directly, or through a representative or an appropriate body, in a manner consistent with the procedural rul
[normal]es of national law’. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Children’s special and dependent status creates real difficulties for them in pursuing remedies for breaches of their rights.  So States need to give particular attention to ensuring that 
[normal]there are effective, child-sensitive procedures available to children and their representatives.  These should include the provision of child-friendly information, advice, advocacy, including support for self-advocacy, and access to independent complaints 
[normal]procedures 
[normal]and to the courts with necessary legal and other assistance[bold].
[normal]&#xa0;
